<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,356,959]" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,465,356,382]" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">Supplemental description.</emphasis>
Micropterous male (n = 1). Body length 3.25; maximum width 0.90. Anterior lobe of pronotum (subtriangular), thoracic pleura, lateral margins of all acetabula, abdominal mediotergites I–III (irregular-shaped), V–VIII (V–VII rounded and increasing posteriorly), anterolateral corners of abdominal laterotergites, and lateral (below abdominal lacunae) and central regions of abdominal sterna III–VI covered by minute, frosty, pubescence, visible mainly in anterior or lateral views (
<figureCitation box="[772,909,500,527]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,489,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-148@9.[151,1436,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. Paravelia spp., (21–26) Paravelia nieseri Moreira &amp; Barbosa, (21) dorsal habitus of female from Serra do Caraça, Brazil (MZUSP), (22) dorsal view of head, (23) fore tibia of male, (24) fore tibia of female, (25) middle tibia of male, black arrow indicates elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae, (26) lateral view of female abdomen. (27–29) Paravelia rotundanotata (Hungerford), (27) dorsal habitus of micropterous male from Paragominas, Brazil (CEIOC), (28) fore tibia and tarsus of male, (29) lateral view of male abdomen. gc = grasping comb, if = impressed furrow, iml = impressed median line, cil = convergent impressed line, pi = posterior indentation, II–VII = abdominal segments." pageId="10" pageNumber="287">Figs. 27, 29</figureCitation>
). Dorsal surface of head, pronotum, abdominal medio- and laterotergites, and lateral region of abdomen with long, dark-brown, generally dispersed, setae. Ocular setae present. Meso- and metasterna centrally with two pairs of small tubercles on intersegmental region. Posterior margin of metasternum convex. Fore tibia (
<quantity box="[644,747,609,635]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.8" pageId="10" pageNumber="287" unit="mm" value="0.98">0.98 mm</quantity>
long) with grasping comb (
<quantity box="[1063,1166,609,635]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7999999999999998" pageId="10" pageNumber="287" unit="mm" value="0.18">0.18 mm</quantity>
long) occupying only a small apical region of segment (
<figureCitation box="[512,597,644,671]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,489,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-148@9.[151,1436,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. Paravelia spp., (21–26) Paravelia nieseri Moreira &amp; Barbosa, (21) dorsal habitus of female from Serra do Caraça, Brazil (MZUSP), (22) dorsal view of head, (23) fore tibia of male, (24) fore tibia of female, (25) middle tibia of male, black arrow indicates elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae, (26) lateral view of female abdomen. (27–29) Paravelia rotundanotata (Hungerford), (27) dorsal habitus of micropterous male from Paragominas, Brazil (CEIOC), (28) fore tibia and tarsus of male, (29) lateral view of male abdomen. gc = grasping comb, if = impressed furrow, iml = impressed median line, cil = convergent impressed line, pi = posterior indentation, II–VII = abdominal segments." pageId="10" pageNumber="287">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
). Middle tibia without row of elongate trichobothria-like setae. Abdominal sterna II–VII laterally with narrow, transverse furrows at anterior regions, and roughly rounded longitudinal furrows at mid-length (
<figureCitation box="[317,401,716,743]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,489,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-148@9.[151,1436,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. Paravelia spp., (21–26) Paravelia nieseri Moreira &amp; Barbosa, (21) dorsal habitus of female from Serra do Caraça, Brazil (MZUSP), (22) dorsal view of head, (23) fore tibia of male, (24) fore tibia of female, (25) middle tibia of male, black arrow indicates elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae, (26) lateral view of female abdomen. (27–29) Paravelia rotundanotata (Hungerford), (27) dorsal habitus of micropterous male from Paragominas, Brazil (CEIOC), (28) fore tibia and tarsus of male, (29) lateral view of male abdomen. gc = grasping comb, if = impressed furrow, iml = impressed median line, cil = convergent impressed line, pi = posterior indentation, II–VII = abdominal segments." pageId="10" pageNumber="287">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="288" pageId="10" pageNumber="287" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,356,959]" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,752,778]" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">Discussion.</emphasis>
A photograph of the dorsal habitus of the macropterous form of this species was provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigues, H. D. D. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F. &amp; Nieser, N. &amp; Chen, P. P. &amp; Melo, A. L. de &amp; Dias-Silva, K. &amp; Giehl, N. F. S." box="[151,416,788,815]" pageId="10" pageNumber="287" pagination="1 - 47" refId="ref7271" refString="Rodrigues, H. D. D., Moreira, F. F. F., Nieser, N., Chen, P. P., Melo, A. L. de, Dias-Silva, K. &amp; Giehl, N. F. S. (2014) The genus Paravelia Breddin, 1898 (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Veliidae) in Brazil, with descriptions of eight new species. Zootaxa, 3784 (1), 1 - 47. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3784.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Rodrigues 
<emphasis box="[274,323,788,814]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">et al</emphasis>
. (2014)
</bibRefCitation>
. Recently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mazzucconi, S. A. &amp; Armua de Reyes, C. &amp; Estevez, A. L." box="[539,822,788,815]" pageId="10" pageNumber="287" pagination="451 - 505" refId="ref6775" refString="Mazzucconi, S. A., Armua de Reyes, C. &amp; Estevez, A. L. (2022) Aquatic and semiaquatic Heteroptera (Insecta: Hemiptera) from Ibera Natural Reserve (Corrientes Province, Argentina). Zootaxa, 5104 (4), 451 - 505. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 5104.4.1" type="journal article" year="2022">
Mazzucconi 
<emphasis box="[683,733,788,814]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">et al</emphasis>
. (2022)
</bibRefCitation>
recorded this species from the Province of 
<collectingRegion box="[1313,1433,788,814]" country="Argentina" name="Corrientes" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">Corrientes</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,265,824,850]" name="Argentina" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, 92 years after its original record from “La Plata” (
<bibRefCitation author="Hungerford, H. B." box="[843,1057,824,851]" pageId="10" pageNumber="287" pagination="120 - 125" refId="ref6660" refString="Hungerford, H. B. (1930 a) Concerning Velia inveruglas Kirkaldy and related forms. (Veliidae-Hemiptera). Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 23, 120 - 125. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / aesa / 23.1.120" type="journal article" year="1930">Hungerford 1930a</bibRefCitation>
). The same authors also offered a photograph of the dorsal habitus of the micropterous male. In the present study, we examined a micropterous male (
<figureCitation box="[159,242,896,923]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,489,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-148@9.[151,1436,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. Paravelia spp., (21–26) Paravelia nieseri Moreira &amp; Barbosa, (21) dorsal habitus of female from Serra do Caraça, Brazil (MZUSP), (22) dorsal view of head, (23) fore tibia of male, (24) fore tibia of female, (25) middle tibia of male, black arrow indicates elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae, (26) lateral view of female abdomen. (27–29) Paravelia rotundanotata (Hungerford), (27) dorsal habitus of micropterous male from Paragominas, Brazil (CEIOC), (28) fore tibia and tarsus of male, (29) lateral view of male abdomen. gc = grasping comb, if = impressed furrow, iml = impressed median line, cil = convergent impressed line, pi = posterior indentation, II–VII = abdominal segments." pageId="10" pageNumber="287">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) collected in the Amazon, State of 
<collectingRegion box="[641,694,897,923]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">Pará</collectingRegion>
, northern 
<collectingCountry box="[809,880,896,922]" name="Brazil" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, the northernmost record of the species known at moment.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,975,1975,1999]" pageId="10" pageNumber="287" startId="10.[151,250,1975,1999]" targetBox="[298,1290,982,1951]" targetPageId="10">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,975,1975,1999]" box="[151,975,1975,1999]" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,288,1975,1999]" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">FIGURE 30.</emphasis>
Distribution records of five species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Breddin" authorityYear="1898" box="[684,784,1975,1999]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="287" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[684,784,1975,1999]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="287">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in South America.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Polhemus" authorityYear="1976" box="[199,477,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rotundanotata">
<emphasis box="[199,477,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">Paravelia rotundanotata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hungerford, 1930)" baseAuthorityName="Hungerford" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[880,1225,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confusa">
<emphasis box="[880,996,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">P. confusa</emphasis>
(Hungerford, 1930)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Rodrigues, Moreira, Nieser, Chen &amp; Melo, 2014" authorityName="Rodrigues, Moreira, Nieser, Chen &amp; Melo" authorityYear="2014" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornata">
<emphasis box="[1282,1386,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">P. ornata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigues, H. D. D. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F. &amp; Nieser, N. &amp; Chen, P. P. &amp; Melo, A. L. de &amp; Dias-Silva, K. &amp; Giehl, N. F. S." pageId="11" pageNumber="288" pagination="1 - 47" refId="ref7271" refString="Rodrigues, H. D. D., Moreira, F. F. F., Nieser, N., Chen, P. P., Melo, A. L. de, Dias-Silva, K. &amp; Giehl, N. F. S. (2014) The genus Paravelia Breddin, 1898 (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Veliidae) in Brazil, with descriptions of eight new species. Zootaxa, 3784 (1), 1 - 47. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3784.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">Rodrigues, Moreira, Nieser, Chen &amp; Melo, 2014</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and these three form a distinct subgroup within the genus. They all share, for example, the pubescence of the body and the maculae pattern on the forewing of the macropterous specimens, in addition to the body covered by small black denticles. It can be separated from these congeners by the absence of projections on male abdominal sternum VII (present in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hungerford" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[893,1007,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confusa">
<emphasis box="[893,1007,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">P. confusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and by the antennomere IV distinctly lighter than the others (
<figureCitation box="[411,493,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,489,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-148@9.[151,1436,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. Paravelia spp., (21–26) Paravelia nieseri Moreira &amp; Barbosa, (21) dorsal habitus of female from Serra do Caraça, Brazil (MZUSP), (22) dorsal view of head, (23) fore tibia of male, (24) fore tibia of female, (25) middle tibia of male, black arrow indicates elongate dark-brown trichobothria-like setae, (26) lateral view of female abdomen. (27–29) Paravelia rotundanotata (Hungerford), (27) dorsal habitus of micropterous male from Paragominas, Brazil (CEIOC), (28) fore tibia and tarsus of male, (29) lateral view of male abdomen. gc = grasping comb, if = impressed furrow, iml = impressed median line, cil = convergent impressed line, pi = posterior indentation, II–VII = abdominal segments." pageId="11" pageNumber="288">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) (concolorous with the others in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rodrigues, Moreira, Nieser, Chen &amp; Melo" authorityYear="2014" box="[863,966,331,356]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornata">
<emphasis box="[863,966,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">P. ornata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">
The term “pruinose areas” 
<emphasis box="[504,566,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigues, H. D. D. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F. &amp; Nieser, N. &amp; Chen, P. P. &amp; Melo, A. L. de &amp; Dias-Silva, K. &amp; Giehl, N. F. S." box="[573,835,367,393]" pageId="11" pageNumber="288" pagination="1 - 47" refId="ref7271" refString="Rodrigues, H. D. D., Moreira, F. F. F., Nieser, N., Chen, P. P., Melo, A. L. de, Dias-Silva, K. &amp; Giehl, N. F. S. (2014) The genus Paravelia Breddin, 1898 (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Veliidae) in Brazil, with descriptions of eight new species. Zootaxa, 3784 (1), 1 - 47. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3784.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Rodrigues 
<emphasis box="[696,753,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">et al.</emphasis>
(2014)
</bibRefCitation>
mentioned for this species is here changed to “frosty pubescence”. Pruinosity is caused by wax particles on the insect’s cuticle that cover up the underlying coloration, giving a dusty or frosted appearance, which does not seem to occur in 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Polhemus" authorityYear="1976" box="[950,1137,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rotundanotata">
<emphasis box="[950,1137,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">P. rotundanotata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In this species, it appears that these whitish regions along the body are formed by a very dense layer of short setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="288" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,510,537]" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
This species is distributed from northern 
<collectingCountry box="[972,1043,511,537]" name="Brazil" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, in the Amazon, to the province of 
<collectingRegion box="[151,302,547,573]" country="Argentina" name="Ciudad Autonoma de Buenos Aires" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">Buenos Aires</collectingRegion>
(La Plata), in 
<collectingCountry box="[463,574,547,573]" name="Argentina" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[590,675,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1975,1999]" captionTargetBox="[298,1290,982,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-292@10.[298,1290,982,1951]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 30. Distribution records of five species of Paravelia in South America." pageId="11" pageNumber="288">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). The records from 
<collectingRegion box="[897,1050,547,573]" country="Brazil" name="Minas Gerais" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">Minas Gerais</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1062,1133,547,573]" name="Brazil" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hungerford, H. B." pageId="11" pageNumber="288" pagination="120 - 125" refId="ref6660" refString="Hungerford, H. B. (1930 a) Concerning Velia inveruglas Kirkaldy and related forms. (Veliidae-Hemiptera). Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 23, 120 - 125. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / aesa / 23.1.120" type="journal article" year="1930">Hungerford (1930a)</bibRefCitation>
were not included in the map due to the absence of precision. The specimen from 
<collectingRegion box="[1147,1200,583,609]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">Pará</collectingRegion>
, northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1311,1382,583,609]" name="Brazil" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, was collected in a stream in a pasture area, without marginal vegetation, whereas that examined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mazzucconi, S. A. &amp; Armua de Reyes, C. &amp; Estevez, A. L." pageId="11" pageNumber="288" pagination="451 - 505" refId="ref6775" refString="Mazzucconi, S. A., Armua de Reyes, C. &amp; Estevez, A. L. (2022) Aquatic and semiaquatic Heteroptera (Insecta: Hemiptera) from Ibera Natural Reserve (Corrientes Province, Argentina). Zootaxa, 5104 (4), 451 - 505. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 5104.4.1" type="journal article" year="2022">
Mazzucconi 
<emphasis box="[1379,1429,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="288">et al</emphasis>
. (2022)
</bibRefCitation>
was collected on the open water surface at the Corriente River, in a shaded place close to emergent vegetation.
</paragraph>
